      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I disagree with Maureen Dowd's take on Michelle Obama's public airing of Barack Obama's domestic dirty laundry (''She's Not Buttering Him Up,'' column, April 25). I think that it is politically brilliant for three reasons:</p>
        <p>First, the glimpse into their daily life projects a marital and familial warmth that categorically and favorably distinguishes him from his main opponent for the Democratic nomination.</p>
        <p>Second, this side of Barack Obama appeals to the ''silent majority'' of married men like me who are equally deficient in the art of bed- and toast-making (and I suspect also to the women who put up with us, although I don't dare ask my wife).</p>
        <p>Third, after six-plus years of a delusional president enabled by a first lady with a painful, stand-by-your-man grin, I find the prospect of a first lady who occasionally ranks on the president to keep his ego in check utterly refreshing.</p>
        <p>Josh Koskoff  Westport, Conn., April 25, 2007</p>
      </block>
